153. Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array
Problem

An array is originally sorted in ascending order and then rotated at an unknown pivot.

All elements are unique.

Find the minimum element in the rotated sorted array.

Example 1
nums = [3,4,5,1,2]

Output = 1

Original Array:

[1,2,3,4,5]

Rotated:

[3,4,5,1,2]
Example 2
nums = [4,5,6,7,0,1,2]

Output = 0
Example 3
nums = [11,13,15,17]

Output = 11

Array is already sorted.

Minimum is the first element.

Key Observation

In a rotated sorted array:

[4,5,6,7,0,1,2]

the minimum element lies exactly at the rotation point.

4 5 6 7 | 0 1 2
          ↑
       minimum

Our goal is to find this point using Binary Search.

Why Not Linear Search?
int min = nums[0];

for(int num : nums){
    min = Math.min(min, num);
}
Complexity
Time = O(n)
Space = O(1)

But the problem requires:

O(log n)

Therefore Binary Search must be used.

Main Idea

Compare:

nums[mid]

with:

nums[high]

This tells us which side contains the minimum element.

Observation 1

If:

nums[mid] > nums[high]

Example:

[4,5,6,7,0,1,2]

mid = 7
high = 2
7 > 2

The minimum must be on the right side.

4 5 6 7 | 0 1 2
          ↑

Move:

low = mid + 1;
Observation 2

If:

nums[mid] < nums[high]

Example:

0 1 2
mid = 1
high = 2
1 < 2

The minimum lies on the left side including mid.

Move:

high = mid;
Why not high = mid - 1?

Because mid itself could be the minimum.

Binary Search Logic
Case 1
if(nums[mid] > nums[high])

Minimum lies in:

[mid+1 ... high]

Move:

low = mid + 1;
Case 2
else

Minimum lies in:

[low ... mid]

Move:

high = mid;
Code
class Solution {

    public int findMin(int[] nums) {

        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;

        while(low < high) {

            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            if(nums[mid] > nums[high]) {
                low = mid + 1;
            }
            else {
                high = mid;
            }
        }

        return nums[low];
    }
}
