Search Left
Why Use while(low < high)?

Unlike standard Binary Search:

while(low <= high)

Here we are not searching for a target.

We are narrowing the search space until:

low == high

At that point:

Both point to the minimum element.
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity

Each iteration eliminates half of the array.

n → n/2 → n/4 → n/8 ...

Therefore:

O(log n)
Space Complexity

Only a few variables are used.

O(1)
Pattern Recognition

Use this pattern when:

Array is sorted and rotated.
Elements are unique.
Need to find minimum element.
O(log n) solution is required.
Key Takeaway

The important insight is:

if(nums[mid] > nums[high])

👉 Minimum lies on the right side.

low = mid + 1;

Otherwise:

high = mid;

👉 Minimum lies on the left side (including mid).

When:

low == high

that index contains the minimum element.
